726306f-c.text:
Calamus Ave., north side, between 72nd Place and 74th Street, showing an old farm house said to be that of Jonathan Hunt in the Seventeen Hundreds. It was in the Pisher family from 1873 to 1891. It does not appear on the 1927 Queens Atlas. This is a set of four views, showing the front of the house. To the right of it are the
overhead lines of the Long Island Railroad.
January 1924.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

726302f-b.text:
Calamus :Ave, north side, between 72nd Place and 74th Street, showing in a set of three views the Jonathan Hunt house of 1700. It had half doors and its partitions were filled with loam and brick.
It was demolished prior to 1927.
May 28, 1925.
Views 2 & 3: April 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

726301f-b.text:
(1)
Calamus Ave., west from 72nd Place, showing the home of J. Brigman
from 1873-1891.
May 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(2)
The same, also showing the house at the S.W. Corner of the above mentioned Streets. Note 72nd Place was formerly Jefferson Ave. There are two Jefferson Aves in this neighborhood. This one is
nearer to the New York Connecting Railroad.
May 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
